# Java Collections Utility Methods – Quick Revision Notes

The `Collections` class provides useful utility methods for working with Java Collections like `ArrayList`, `LinkedList`, etc.

```java
import java.util.Collections;
```

---

## 1. `Collections.sort(list)`

Sorts the list in **ascending order**.

### Example

```java
ArrayList<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>();

list.add(30);
list.add(10);
list.add(20);

Collections.sort(list);

System.out.println(list);
```

### Output

```java
[10, 20, 30]
```

### Time Complexity

```text
O(n log n)
```

### Common Uses

- Sorting arrays/lists
- Binary Search preparation
- Greedy algorithms

---

## 2. `Collections.reverse(list)`

Reverses the order of elements.

### Example

```java
ArrayList<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>();

list.add(10);
list.add(20);
list.add(30);

Collections.reverse(list);

System.out.println(list);
```

### Output

```java
[30, 20, 10]
```

### Time Complexity

```text
O(n)
```

### Common Uses

- Reverse traversal
- String/List manipulation
- Two-pointer problems

---

## 3. `Collections.max(list)`

Returns the largest element.

### Example

```java
ArrayList<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>();

list.add(10);
list.add(50);
list.add(20);

System.out.println(Collections.max(list));
```

### Output

```java
50
```

### Time Complexity

```text
O(n)
```

### Common Uses

- Finding maximum value
- Competitive programming

---

## 4. `Collections.min(list)`

Returns the smallest element.

### Example

```java
ArrayList<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>();

list.add(10);
list.add(50);
list.add(20);

System.out.println(Collections.min(list));
```

### Output

```java
10
```

### Time Complexity

```text
O(n)
```

### Common Uses

- Finding minimum value
- Optimization problems

---

## 5. `Collections.frequency(list, obj)`

Counts how many times an object appears.

### Example

```java
ArrayList<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>();

list.add(10);
list.add(20);
list.add(10);
list.add(30);
list.add(10);

System.out.println(Collections.frequency(list, 10));
```

### Output

```java
3
```

### Time Complexity

```text
O(n)
```

### Common Uses

- Counting occurrences
- Frequency-based problems

---

## 6. `Collections.shuffle(list)`

Randomly rearranges elements.

### Example

```java
ArrayList<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>();

list.add(1);
list.add(2);
list.add(3);
list.add(4);

Collections.shuffle(list);

System.out.println(list);
```

### Possible Outputs

```java
[3, 1, 4, 2]
```

```java
[2, 4, 1, 3]
```

```java
[4, 3, 2, 1]
```

### Time Complexity

```text
O(n)
```

### Common Uses

- Randomization
- Games
- Test data generation

